  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou1-cpb-not-accepted-20260419",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/credibility-assessment-team-uofa",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Not accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CFD hemolysis prediction for CPB application, MRL 2) is NOT ACCEPTED. The primary basis for rejection is the Discretization Error factor, which achieved Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3. Specifically: (1) The grid convergence index for the hemolysis index QOI at the critical 4500 RPM / 5 L/min operating point is 8.3%, exceeding the 5% threshold required for Gradation 3. (2) The apparent order of accuracy (p = 1.4) is below the nominal scheme order (p = 2), indicating the solution has not entered the asymptotic convergence regime on any of the three mesh levels tested. (3) The hemolysis index is highly sensitive to the shear stress field in the impeller tip clearance region, where mesh resolution is most deficient. Because the discretization error is insufficiently controlled for the primary QOI, the validation comparison results (Output Comparison factor, Gradation 3) cannot be interpreted with confidence — the numerical uncertainty contribution to the 12.4% mean absolute error is not separable from model form error. All other assessed factors (Software Quality Assurance, Numerical Code Verification, Test Conditions, Output Comparison, Relevance of QOI, Relevance of Validation Activities) meet or exceed their required levels. Six factors are appropriately scoped out at MRL 2 with documented rationale. To achieve acceptance, the submitter must: (a) generate a fourth, finer mesh level sufficient to demonstrate asymptotic convergence (GCI < 5% for hemolysis index at all 5 operating points), or (b) apply Richardson extrapolation with demonstrated p ≥ 1.8 and report extrapolated values with quantified numerical uncertainty bounds, or (c) provide a justified argument that the current GCI is acceptable given the specific COU decision criterion (RH < 1) with a sensitivity analysis demonstrating that the hemolysis index uncertainty does not alter the worst-case identification.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
